WEBVTT

00:02.300 --> 00:02.533
- Previously

00:02.533 --> 00:03.066
- Previously
on "Southern Charm"...

00:05.000 --> 00:06.300
I'm free!
- [cheering]

00:06.300 --> 00:08.166
- That's right, this new mom

00:08.166 --> 00:10.166
finally got some time off
for good behavior.

00:10.166 --> 00:11.433
- Damn it!

00:11.433 --> 00:13.233
- Meanwhile,
Craig's bad habits

00:13.233 --> 00:15.700
caused Patricia
to give him the boot.

00:15.700 --> 00:18.033
- It's been two months.

00:18.033 --> 00:19.500
I think we have to table it.

00:19.500 --> 00:21.433
[dramatic music]

00:21.433 --> 00:24.033
- Which is exactly what Ashley
might be giving Thomas.

00:24.033 --> 00:25.033
- They used to call
me the wolf,

00:25.033 --> 00:26.400
you know, when I was single.

00:26.400 --> 00:28.667
- It might not be long
until you're single again.

00:28.667 --> 00:31.233
- Or maybe it's
the other way around.

00:31.233 --> 00:33.433
- Sometimes, I feel like
you get a little needy.

00:33.433 --> 00:35.433
You need to be grounded
in who you are.

00:35.433 --> 00:38.333
That's the person
I'm wanting to marry.

00:38.333 --> 00:40.467
- And after Victoria
heard about

00:40.467 --> 00:42.467
Austen's hug and
twirl with Chelsea,

00:42.467 --> 00:45.133
their breakup was inevitable.

00:45.133 --> 00:47.066
- I mean, Shep, she, uh,

00:47.066 --> 00:49.734
she tossed a drink at me.
Boom!

00:49.734 --> 00:52.033
- However, it was Kathryn
that had everyone

00:52.033 --> 00:53.467
on pins and needles
when she disappeared.

00:53.467 --> 00:55.266
- I hope that she's not

00:55.266 --> 00:57.066
drinking or doing drugs.

00:57.066 --> 00:58.200
[knocking on door]

00:58.200 --> 00:59.734
Kathryn, open the door.

00:59.734 --> 01:01.166
What the (BLEEP)
is wrong with her?

01:01.166 --> 01:02.533
- Call the police.

01:02.533 --> 01:04.066
- But turns out
she went off the grid

01:04.066 --> 01:05.333
not because she was on drugs,

01:05.333 --> 01:07.300
but because she went off them.

01:07.300 --> 01:09.033
- I thought to myself

01:09.033 --> 01:11.333
I don't need these meds
for depression.

01:11.333 --> 01:13.333
- I don't want you
to ever feel like you can't

01:13.333 --> 01:15.033
come to me about something.

01:15.033 --> 01:16.333
- I know you wouldn't judge me.

01:16.333 --> 01:18.300
It was just a matter of,
like, confronting it.

01:18.300 --> 01:20.200
- ♪ Times have changed ♪

01:20.200 --> 01:22.367
♪ Don't you know?
Don't you know? ♪

01:22.367 --> 01:24.433
♪ Mm-hmm ♪

01:25.367 --> 01:28.367
[bright jazz music]

01:28.367 --> 01:35.433
♪ ♪

01:40.166 --> 01:42.300
- Perfect!

01:42.300 --> 01:44.500
- Oh, damn it.
I forgot about the butter.

01:44.500 --> 01:45.734
Huh.

01:45.734 --> 01:48.233
I forgot the panko!

01:48.233 --> 01:50.266
Jesus, this is bad.

01:52.100 --> 01:55.100
[mischievous orchestral music]

01:55.100 --> 02:00.100
♪ ♪

02:00.500 --> 02:02.200
- What do I want to make?

02:02.200 --> 02:09.200
♪ ♪

02:15.333 --> 02:16.533
Hey, Sean!

02:16.533 --> 02:18.000
- What?

02:18.000 --> 02:19.533
- This one-handed thing sucks!

02:19.533 --> 02:21.133
Would you just
please come help me?

02:21.133 --> 02:24.333
I can't do sh-- with this!

02:24.333 --> 02:27.400
To me, deadlines
are arbitrary a lot of times.

02:27.400 --> 02:29.400
Patricia could've
given me one more night,

02:29.400 --> 02:32.000
and she'd have
a badass pillow concept.

02:32.000 --> 02:35.367
But you know,
it was a "principle thing."

02:35.367 --> 02:37.200
- So what is
this thing gonna do?

02:37.200 --> 02:39.333
- I'm making a pillowcase.

02:39.333 --> 02:41.467
You know,
maybe it's for the better.

02:41.467 --> 02:44.033
You know, I don't think
I could work for someone else,

02:44.033 --> 02:46.400
and who knows where
we would've ended up.

02:46.400 --> 02:47.567
I'm guessing that
you're not gonna

02:47.567 --> 02:49.133
want to help me all day long.

02:49.133 --> 02:50.633
- Yeah, it's probably a no.

02:50.633 --> 02:52.433
- [chuckles]

02:52.433 --> 02:55.433
[upbeat jazzy music]

02:55.433 --> 03:00.500
♪ ♪

03:00.500 --> 03:03.166
- Oh my God!
What is that smell?

03:03.166 --> 03:05.033
Is something on fire?

03:05.033 --> 03:06.266
- [chuckles]

03:06.266 --> 03:07.367
- It's, like, smoky in here.

03:07.367 --> 03:09.367
There's, like,
a haze in the air.

03:09.367 --> 03:11.033
- How are you?
- Good, how are you?

03:11.033 --> 03:12.033
- Good to see you.

03:12.033 --> 03:13.166
- The house looks great.

03:13.166 --> 03:15.033
- Oh yeah!
Check it out!

03:15.033 --> 03:17.166
[cheerful jazz music]

03:17.166 --> 03:18.300
- I like it!

03:18.300 --> 03:20.033
It's chic.
- Thank you.

03:20.033 --> 03:21.433
- For real, what did you burn?
- All right.

03:21.433 --> 03:23.433
I'm trying to make meatballs.
Will you help me?

03:23.433 --> 03:25.166
I don't know what I'm doing.

03:25.166 --> 03:26.300
- Okay, well,
what's this called?

03:26.300 --> 03:27.467
Craftsy.com?

03:27.467 --> 03:29.066
What is this, like a site

03:29.066 --> 03:30.400
that tells you how to cook?

03:30.400 --> 03:31.533
- It's meatballs.

03:31.533 --> 03:34.533
You know what
I think I'm missing?

03:34.533 --> 03:35.700
[both chuckle]

03:35.700 --> 03:38.333
Can you tie this?

03:38.333 --> 03:39.600
- Are you gaining weight?
- What?

03:39.600 --> 03:41.200
- You sure have some handles.

03:41.200 --> 03:43.200
- Can you handle it?

03:43.200 --> 03:44.200
Do you want a glass of wine?

03:44.200 --> 03:45.600
- Yes.
- Okay.

03:45.600 --> 03:47.467
- Was the instruction to put
the whole garlic clove in,

03:47.467 --> 03:49.300
or were you supposed
to mince them?

03:49.300 --> 03:51.600
- I don't mince words,
and I don't mince garlic.

03:51.600 --> 03:53.400
- Are you drunk right now?

03:53.400 --> 03:55.200
- [soft scoff]
That's so rude.

03:55.200 --> 03:57.266
I'm overwhelmed.

03:57.266 --> 03:59.066
Look at me.

03:59.066 --> 04:00.600
- That's great.
Thank you so much.

04:00.600 --> 04:02.700
- How's Palmer?
- Palmer's great.

04:02.700 --> 04:05.400
She's with my mom
right now asleep.

04:05.400 --> 04:07.300
I do feel a little bit

04:07.300 --> 04:09.233
guilty being out

04:09.233 --> 04:10.633
without my child.

04:10.633 --> 04:13.100
- Is your mom happy
for having a little grandchild?

04:13.100 --> 04:14.367
- She's very happy.

04:14.367 --> 04:17.100
But I have to balance
being a mother

04:17.100 --> 04:19.500
with also still
having my own life.

04:19.500 --> 04:22.200
Because babies, they're like,

04:22.200 --> 04:23.367
they're just little parasites.

04:23.367 --> 04:25.734
And you're
their personal assistant.

04:25.734 --> 04:28.200
Let's look at the
printed-off directions.

04:28.200 --> 04:30.367
I think what we need to do
at this point

04:30.367 --> 04:32.300
is just have a clean canvas
and start over.

04:32.300 --> 04:35.166
Do you have another pan?

04:35.166 --> 04:36.567
- Yes, I do.
- Okay.

04:38.734 --> 04:41.367
You need to really get pants

04:41.367 --> 04:43.734
that fit your waist, because
every time you bend over,

04:43.734 --> 04:45.500
I have to see your ass crack.
- I don't have a butt.

04:45.500 --> 04:47.100
- Crack is whack.

04:47.100 --> 04:48.266
Yeah.

04:48.266 --> 04:49.533
God knows when the last time

04:49.533 --> 04:51.533
he has washed it,
or where it has been.

04:51.533 --> 04:53.467
[playful music]

04:53.467 --> 04:56.400
Do you have, like,
a wooden spoon?

04:56.400 --> 04:58.367
Something that's not plastic?

04:58.367 --> 05:00.133
- Yeah...

05:00.133 --> 05:01.533
- When you have raw meat in
your hands,

05:01.533 --> 05:04.100
you don't touch things.
- Okay.

05:04.100 --> 05:05.533
What do I know?
I don't know anything.

05:05.533 --> 05:07.333
- This is really--
- My mom has done everything

05:07.333 --> 05:09.266
for me for my whole life.
- That's sad.

05:09.266 --> 05:13.133
I thought I was useless
in the kitchen.

05:13.133 --> 05:15.266
- You're gonna put salt
and pepper all over that.

05:15.266 --> 05:18.533
♪ ♪

05:18.533 --> 05:20.767
- Twist it?

05:20.767 --> 05:22.266
But at least I can, like,

05:22.266 --> 05:24.266
read a recipe and follow it.

05:24.266 --> 05:26.266
"Add 3/4 of a cup cheese."

05:26.266 --> 05:29.266
Please do not sever
your finger like Craig did.

05:29.266 --> 05:30.400
- [laughs]

05:30.400 --> 05:31.533
- "Crumble in the ground beef."

05:31.533 --> 05:33.400
- Craig would be
really good at this.

05:33.400 --> 05:35.500
- Put a little oil in there.
- Mm-hmm.

05:35.500 --> 05:37.400
- So tell me about Craig.
How's he doing?

05:37.400 --> 05:38.700
I haven't seen him in forever.

05:38.700 --> 05:40.367
- He made out with this chick.

05:40.367 --> 05:41.633
- He did?
- Mm-hmm.

05:41.633 --> 05:43.367
Austen had to beg him to do it.

05:43.367 --> 05:44.633
He's like, "Kiss her!"

05:44.633 --> 05:46.166
- We started playing,
you know, music,

05:46.166 --> 05:47.500
to like, put them in the mood.

05:47.500 --> 05:49.567
And the one that
we played on repeat was

05:49.567 --> 05:50.633
"The Little Mermaid."

05:50.633 --> 05:52.000
It was like:

05:52.000 --> 05:53.533
♪ You gotta kiss the girl ♪

05:53.533 --> 05:54.767
- When they finally kissed,

05:54.767 --> 05:56.700
Craig was like,
"Eh, I didn't like it."

05:56.700 --> 05:58.500
- Craig's such a girl.

05:58.500 --> 06:00.166
I think it's done.

06:00.166 --> 06:02.400
This is something that
you could do for a date.

06:02.400 --> 06:04.000
- Yeah, if I wanted
to get rid of her.

06:04.000 --> 06:06.433
- [chuckles]

06:06.433 --> 06:08.500
- All right, I know
you're a proponent of me

06:08.500 --> 06:10.300
being, like, go find a girl.

06:10.300 --> 06:11.700
I just don't want you
to worry about me.

06:11.700 --> 06:13.200
- I don't worry about you.

06:13.200 --> 06:15.033
♪ ♪

06:15.033 --> 06:17.734
All right, we'll share a plate,
like "Lady and the Tramp."

06:17.734 --> 06:19.333
- Who's the tramp?

06:19.333 --> 06:21.734
- You.

06:21.734 --> 06:23.600
Honestly, if being
in a relationship

06:23.600 --> 06:25.200
is not important to you,

06:25.200 --> 06:27.033
I don't think you need
to be in any rush.

06:27.033 --> 06:28.734
I think where you are
in your life right now

06:28.734 --> 06:30.300
is a very good place.

06:30.300 --> 06:31.467
You're content.

06:31.467 --> 06:32.467
- I don't know.

06:32.467 --> 06:35.400
Should I just marry Kathryn?

06:35.400 --> 06:36.633
[chuckles]

06:38.200 --> 06:41.200
[jazzy guitar music]

06:41.200 --> 06:44.333
♪ ♪

06:44.333 --> 06:46.533
[bell rings]

06:46.533 --> 06:47.700
- You rang, madam?

06:47.700 --> 06:50.533
- Oh, Michael,
Thomas is coming over.

06:50.533 --> 06:52.400
- Shall I poach
some shrimp in butter?

06:52.400 --> 06:53.633
- I'd say let's just wait.

06:53.633 --> 06:55.467
Let's just give him a cocktail

06:55.467 --> 06:57.233
and see what's going on.

06:57.233 --> 06:59.367
- Certainly.
- Okay, thank you.

06:59.367 --> 07:02.333
[bright music]

07:02.333 --> 07:04.233
♪ ♪

07:04.233 --> 07:05.467
[clacking]

07:07.367 --> 07:08.500
- Good evening, sir.
- Michael!

07:08.500 --> 07:10.500
- Good to see you again.

07:10.500 --> 07:11.700
Ms. Altschul is waiting for you
in the double drawing room.

07:11.700 --> 07:13.333
- Oh, good.

07:13.333 --> 07:15.333
Hello, how are you?
- There he is.

07:15.333 --> 07:18.433
Hey, darling.
- Good to see you.

07:18.433 --> 07:19.633
- Let's get you a cocktail.

07:19.633 --> 07:21.367
- Yeah.
- What would you like?

07:21.367 --> 07:24.333
- I'm gonna have
what they refer to as

07:24.333 --> 07:25.633
a Hampton's Gatorade.

07:25.633 --> 07:27.567
- What's that?
- Rosé.

07:27.567 --> 07:28.633
- I'll take one too.
- Very good.

07:28.633 --> 07:30.433
- Michael, do me a favor.

07:30.433 --> 07:33.367
I just finished
the guest list for the ball.

07:33.367 --> 07:34.633
Would you please
give it to Joan?

07:34.633 --> 07:36.367
- Certainly.

07:36.367 --> 07:38.233
- So you'll be getting
yours shortly.

07:38.233 --> 07:39.500
- Great.
- It's gonna be a

07:39.500 --> 07:41.500
winter wonderland ball.
- Mm-hmm.

07:41.500 --> 07:43.400
- You have to wear tails.

07:43.400 --> 07:46.367
Which means
the guys wear tails,

07:46.367 --> 07:48.266
and a different kind of vest.

07:48.266 --> 07:50.667
And the women have to
wear long gowns.

07:50.667 --> 07:53.266
They cannot come
in cocktail attire.

07:53.266 --> 07:55.667
I'm gonna count on you
out there on the dance floor.

07:55.667 --> 07:58.000
- Hopefully, my foot
will be healed by then.

07:58.000 --> 07:59.400
- What's wrong with your foot?

07:59.400 --> 08:00.667
- Well, you know,
I've been playing polo.

08:00.667 --> 08:02.667
- Yeah.
- And I fell off the polo pony

08:02.667 --> 08:04.333
the other day.
- Oh my God.

08:04.333 --> 08:06.100
- Are you coming
to the polo match?

08:06.100 --> 08:07.734
- Maybe.
When is it going to be?

08:07.734 --> 08:10.533
- Sunday. Actually,
I want to get out of polo.

08:10.533 --> 08:12.533
- Well, you know,
you've got children now,

08:12.533 --> 08:14.500
and polo is dangerous.

08:14.500 --> 08:16.633
- But I just figured, you know,

08:16.633 --> 08:18.700
one last hurrah.

08:18.700 --> 08:21.700
I've been under a lot
of pressure to give up polo.

08:21.700 --> 08:24.133
- Don't push your
luck now, Thomas.

08:24.133 --> 08:25.633
If you get hit in the head,

08:25.633 --> 08:27.533
and then we have to put
you in the ground,

08:27.533 --> 08:29.500
who gonna raise those children?

08:29.500 --> 08:30.700
- Mm-hmm.

08:30.700 --> 08:31.700
Take anything in life,

08:31.700 --> 08:33.266
when you get something,

08:33.266 --> 08:37.033
you have to give something up.

08:37.033 --> 08:39.633
- I don't know if I should
bring this up or not,

08:39.633 --> 08:40.767
but you know, Ashley

08:40.767 --> 08:43.300
did come and talk to me.
- Uh-huh.

08:43.300 --> 08:45.400
- I think she was
having a hard time.

08:45.400 --> 08:47.700
- I really think he has
a good thing here, Patricia.

08:47.700 --> 08:50.300
And I think he's--
he's pushing--

08:50.300 --> 08:53.433
he's testing me to see how far
he can push me, you know?

08:53.433 --> 08:55.033
And in those moments,

08:55.033 --> 08:57.033
sometimes, I cry.

08:57.033 --> 08:59.066
- I think there's an unevenness

08:59.066 --> 09:00.567
in terms of what I give her

09:00.567 --> 09:02.467
versus what she's giving me.

09:02.467 --> 09:04.567
That creates resentment
on both parties.

09:04.567 --> 09:06.300
- Mm.
- And I feel like the way

09:06.300 --> 09:09.033
to level the playing field
is for her to work,

09:09.033 --> 09:11.066
you know,
be financially secure.

09:11.066 --> 09:14.433
And if she were focused on
something other than me...

09:14.433 --> 09:16.667
- I told her that's
what she should do.

09:16.667 --> 09:18.467
- But she doesn't
want to do it.

09:18.467 --> 09:19.734
And I'm like...

09:19.734 --> 09:21.333
You know, I asked her one time,

09:21.333 --> 09:23.533
I said, you know,
"What do you see in me?

09:23.533 --> 09:24.734
Why do you love me so much?"

09:24.734 --> 09:26.567
She said,
"Well, you're a good provider."

09:26.567 --> 09:28.600
[dramatic music]

09:28.600 --> 09:31.467
- Which translates into

09:31.467 --> 09:32.734
"You've got money."

09:32.734 --> 09:36.734
Well, no job,
no interests, no friends,

09:36.734 --> 09:39.600
just hanging out
in an apartment

09:39.600 --> 09:42.033
that Thomas pays for.

09:42.033 --> 09:45.033
The word that comes to mind is

09:45.033 --> 09:46.633
"gold digger."

09:46.633 --> 09:50.700
- Yeah, but is this
what I really want?

09:50.700 --> 09:52.767
- Well, you're either
gonna have to

09:52.767 --> 09:54.500
make a commitment,

09:54.500 --> 09:56.667
or cut her loose.

09:58.367 --> 09:59.734
- Coming up...

09:59.734 --> 10:01.467
- I think we should go to

10:01.467 --> 10:04.500
Patricia's winter wonderland.

10:04.500 --> 10:06.033
- Are you asking me out?

10:09.767 --> 10:10.367
[cheerful classical music]

10:12.633 --> 10:16.066
♪ ♪

10:16.066 --> 10:17.600
- Hello.

10:17.600 --> 10:19.166
- Hi, how are you?

10:19.166 --> 10:20.600
- Hi, how are you?
- Good.

10:20.600 --> 10:22.734
- Good to see you.
- Good to see you.

10:22.734 --> 10:25.400
- I got something
for the both of us.

10:25.400 --> 10:27.233
Corn dogs that I got us.
[chuckles]

10:28.667 --> 10:30.667
- I haven't had that
since I was little.

10:30.667 --> 10:32.734
Kind of appropriate
for being on the pier.

10:32.734 --> 10:33.734
Cheers.

10:33.734 --> 10:35.367
[laughing]

10:35.367 --> 10:36.667
[cheerful music]

10:36.667 --> 10:38.133
How is your knee, by the way?

10:38.133 --> 10:39.633
- Knee's doing great!

10:39.633 --> 10:41.133
I able to ride a bike,

10:41.133 --> 10:42.533
so we need to do that.

10:42.533 --> 10:44.734
- I gotta buy one, though.

10:44.734 --> 10:46.633
[both shout]

10:46.633 --> 10:47.667
- What the (BLEEP)?

10:47.667 --> 10:49.133
- That was really aggressive.

10:49.133 --> 10:51.233
- Am I gonna get
the avian bird flu?

10:51.233 --> 10:53.400
- [chuckles]

10:53.400 --> 10:55.500
Oh my God.

10:55.500 --> 10:57.133
- I'm not gonna eat off
where the bird ate.

10:57.133 --> 10:59.400
[both chuckling]

10:59.400 --> 11:01.000
- Anyways...

11:01.000 --> 11:04.033
- I'm sorry about--to hear
about, like, the last week.

11:04.033 --> 11:05.567
Everybody was worried that you

11:05.567 --> 11:08.400
had fallen off the wagon,
and all this different stuff.

11:08.400 --> 11:10.567
- See, the thing is
it had nothing to do with,

11:10.567 --> 11:12.033
like, alcohol or weed.

11:12.033 --> 11:14.166
It's simply, like,
I fell off the grid

11:14.166 --> 11:17.667
because I deal with depression
and I stopped taking

11:17.667 --> 11:20.133
like, my meds that one week,
because I thought I was good.

11:20.133 --> 11:21.567
- Okay.
- And, like, I knew

11:21.567 --> 11:23.433
everyone's immediate,
like, go-to is,

11:23.433 --> 11:25.166
"Oh, she went to rehab,
it must be

11:25.166 --> 11:27.033
she fell off the wagon,"
you know?

11:27.033 --> 11:28.567
And it sucks...
- Yeah, I know, I know.

11:28.567 --> 11:30.033
- Because it's, like,
it's not even a problem...

11:30.033 --> 11:31.633
- I know.
- But it's, like, my label.

11:31.633 --> 11:35.433
- I mean, I thought
it was drugs and alcohol.

11:35.433 --> 11:37.433
To analyze the present,

11:37.433 --> 11:40.166
one has to look at the past.

